comments.text:
Thanks for the lesson +MrGerter1.  

Might want to check this out:  
http://blog.oxforddictionaries.com/2012/02/grammar-myths-3/

Particularly:  
"Here’s where things are less clear cut: there’s a second type of double 
negative that’s considered correct. In this category, two negatives are 
used in the same sentence or clause to express a positive idea rather than 
a negative one. For instance, in the sentence:

Blake was not unaware of his appearance.

the writer is using two negatives to say in a subtle and indirect way that 
Blake was in fact very aware of his appearance. This sort of double 
negative with a positive result is an aspect of the rhetorical technique 
known as litotes, in which deliberate understatement or denial is used to 
reinforce a statement. The double negative creates a nuance of meaning that 
would not be present had the writer just made an affirmative statement such 
as:

Blake was aware of his appearance."
comments.author: Benjamin Englesmith

comments.author: Frank Spencer

comments.text:
+Darryl Collins Yeah--you can get the book on Amazon. It's been translated 
into English---and it actually spends a lot more time discussing the 
characters, their backstories and why they react the way they do. It's 
basically pointed to as the Japanese "Lord of the Flies". I read the book 
after I saw the movie---the movie isn't really all that 
introspective---it's focused more on the spectacle. But the book has a lot 
more substance to it. (And in the movie there's this weird...side thing 
with the teacher being obsessed with one of the females [because, 
Japan]....but in the book, there's none of that, thankfully.)

Here's the wiki on the book: 
http://battleroyale.wikia.com/wiki/Battle_Royale_(novel)

I've never read the manga or watched the anime--the book is definitely 
worth reading though. It was superior to the movie, definitely.
comments.author: sailtheplains

comments.author: Darryl Collins

comments.text:
+Darryl Collins I read Battle Royale when I was a teenager. The book is 
excellent and the live-action movie is a blast--I've never read the manga 
or seen the anime but I hear they're both based on the original book. When 
I first heard about the Hunger Games--I was expecting Battle Royale. But 
definitely was not the case. BR is just straight up pure brutality. So when 
people were complaining about the violence in HG, I was like: what are they 
talking about? Hahaha.

BR is definitely worth reading--the original book is excellent. And the 
first movie--while it changed some things--is still fun to watch.
